{"title_page": "George Gilbert Scott Jr.", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2020}}\n{{EngvarB|date=January 2020}}\n[[File:Norwich RC Cathedral.jpg|thumb|[[St John the Baptist Cathedral, Norwich]] (RC)]]\n'''George Gilbert Scott Jr.''' (8 October 1839 \u2013 6 May 1897) was an English architect working in late Gothic and Queen Anne revival styles.\n\nKnown in later life as 'Middle Scott', he was the eldest son of Sir Gilbert Scott ([[George Gilbert Scott]]), and father of Sir [[Giles Gilbert Scott]] and [[Adrian Gilbert Scott]], all also architects.\n\nThe last years of his life after the death of his father were marred by mental instability and excessive drinking. He died in the [[Midland Grand Hotel]], St Pancras, a building designed by his father, of [[cirrhosis of the liver]].\n\n==Biography==\n[[File:Gilbert Scott house.jpg|thumb|Gilbert Scott houses in [[The Avenues, Hull]]]]\nScott was born on 8 October 1839, in London, eldest son of Sir [[George Gilbert Scott]] and Caroline Oldrid. After a scholarship at [[Eton College]], he began training at his father's office. He later obtained a [[Cambridge University]] degree in moral sciences at [[Jesus College, Cambridge|Jesus College]] in 1866.{{sfn|Stamp|2004|loc=para.1}}\n\nDuring the 1860 and 1870s he worked for his father in his architectural practice.{{sfn|Stamp|2004|loc=para.2}} He married Ellen King Sampson in the 1870s.{{sfn|Stamp|2004|loc=para.1}}\n\nHe founded [[Watts & Co.|Watts & Company]] in 1874 along with two other leading 19th century architects: [[George Frederick Bodley]] (the architect of [[Washington National Cathedral]]) and [[Thomas Garner]].\n\nAmong the buildings he designed was [[St John the Baptist Cathedral, Norwich|St John the Baptist Church, Norwich]], which became a [[Roman Catholic]] cathedral.{{sfn|Stamp|2004|loc = para.3}} He was also responsible for buildings in three of the [[University of Cambridge]]'s colleges: [[Christ's College, Cambridge|Christ's]], [[Pembroke College, Cambridge|Pembroke]] and [[Peterhouse, Cambridge|Peterhouse]].<ref>{{citation| url = http://www.cambridge2000.com/cambridge2000/html/architect_builder/George_Gilbert_Scott_the_younger.html |work = Cambridge 2000 project|title= George Gilbert Scott, the younger|accessdate = October 2013}}</ref> He masterminded the main buildings of [[Dulwich College]] in South London. Some of his finest works, the churches of All Hallows, Southwark (1877), and [[St Agnes, Kennington Park|St Agnes, Kennington]] (1880) were destroyed by [[Second World War]] bombing.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://southwark.anglican.org/downloads/lostchurches/KEN03.pdf|title=lost churches of southwark|website=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://londonhistorygroup.com/archives/listings/all-hallows-church-southwark|title=All Hallows church, Southwark|website=|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180509051708/http://londonhistorygroup.com/archives/listings/all-hallows-church-southwark|archive-date=9 May 2018|url-status=dead}}</ref> His best remaining residential work is found in the [[The Avenues, Hull|Avenues area of Kingston upon Hull]], which are in a Queen Anne revival style.<ref name=\"a\">{{citation|url=http://www.hullcc.gov.uk/pls/portal/docs/PAGE/HOME/PLANNING/CONSERVATION/CONSERVATION%20AREAS/AVENUES%20CACA.PDF|title=Urban Conservation and Design: Avenues/Pearson Park Conservation Area: Character Statement for the Avenues part of the above area|publisher=Government of the United Kingdom|accessdate=14 August 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120404031939/http://www.hullcc.gov.uk/pls/portal/docs/PAGE/HOME/PLANNING/CONSERVATION/CONSERVATION%20AREAS/AVENUES%20CACA.PDF|archive-date=4 April 2012|url-status=dead}}</ref> Much of his work was in the [[Queen Anne revival]] style, or in imitation of later Gothic architectural styles.{{sfn|Stamp|2004|loc=para.3 & 4}}\n\nAfter his father died in 1878 he became distant from the architectural business, and was supported by his inheritance.{{sfn|Stamp|2004|loc=para.3}} In 1880 Scott became a [[Roman Catholic]], to the shock of his family. The later part of his life saw his mental stability questioned, and in 1883 he was placed in [[Bethlem Hospital]]. A petition of his brothers and wife resulted in his being found of unsound mind in a public examination in 1884. He escaped to [[Rouen]] in France but, returning to England in 1885, he was confined to hospital again in 1885 and 1891-2.{{sfn|Stamp|2004|loc=paras.5 & 6}}\n\nScott died on 6 May 1897 from [[cirrhosis of the liver]] whilst in residence in the [[Midland Grand Hotel]], St Pancras, which had been designed by his father, and was buried on 11 May 1897 at [[St John-at-Hampstead]].{{sfn|Stamp|2004|loc=para.7}}\n\nHe had six children, four of whom survived past childhood \u2013 two of his sons, Sir [[Giles Gilbert Scott]] and [[Adrian Gilbert Scott]], went on to become noted architects.{{sfn|Stamp|2004|loc=para.7}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Sources==\n*{{Citation\n| title  =Scott, George Gilbert (1839\u20131897), architect and scholar\n|first = Gavin| last = Stamp\n| work = The Oxford Dictionary of National Biography \n| doi = 10.1093/ref:odnb/60773 \n| year = 2004 \n|ref =harv\n}}\n*{{Cite book |author=Stamp, Gavin |authorlink=Gavin Stamp |title=An Architect of Promise: George Gilbert Scott Jr and the Late Gothic Revival |year=2002 |publisher=Shaun Tyas |location= |isbn=978-1-900289-51-1 |page=}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|George Gilbert Scott Junior}}\n*[https://www.theguardian.com/arts/critic/feature/0,1169,856635,00.html Profile of George Gilbert Scott, Jr. in ''The Guardian'']\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Scott, George Gilbert Jr.}}\n[[Category:1839 births]]\n[[Category:1897 deaths]]\n[[Category:People educated at Eton College]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Jesus College, Cambridge]]\n[[Category:Scott family (architects)|George Gilbert Jr.]]\n[[Category:History of mental health in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Deaths from cirrhosis]]\n[[Category:Disease-related deaths in England]]\n[[Category:Gothic Revival architects]]\n[[Category:English ecclesiastical architects]]\n[[Category:English Roman Catholics]]\n[[Category:Converts to Roman Catholicism]]\n[[Category:19th-century English architects]]\n[[Category:Architects from London]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2020}}\n{{EngvarB|date=January 2020}}\n[[File:Norwich RC Cathedral.jpg|thumb|[[St John the Baptist Cathedral, Norwich]] (RC)]]\n'''George Gilbert Scott Jr.''' (8 October 1839 \u2013 6 May 1897) was an English architect working in late Gothic and Queen Anne revival styles.\n\nKnown in later life as 'Middle Scott', he was the eldest son of Sir [[George Gilbert Scott]], and father of Sir [[Giles Gilbert Scott]] and [[Adrian Gilbert Scott]], all also architects.\n\nThe last years of his life after the death of his father were marred by mental instability and excessive drinking. He died in the [[Midland Grand Hotel]], St Pancras, a building designed by his father, of [[cirrhosis of the liver]].\n\n==Biography==\n[[File:Gilbert Scott house.jpg|thumb|Gilbert Scott houses in [[The Avenues, Hull]]]]\nScott was born on 8 October 1839, in London, eldest son of Sir [[George Gilbert Scott]] and Caroline Oldrid. After a scholarship at [[Eton College]], he began training at his father's office. He later obtained a [[Cambridge University]] degree in moral sciences at [[Jesus College, Cambridge|Jesus College]] in 1866.{{sfn|Stamp|2004|loc=para.1}}\n\nDuring the 1860 and 1870s he worked for his father in his architectural practice.{{sfn|Stamp|2004|loc=para.2}} He married Ellen King Sampson in the 1870s.{{sfn|Stamp|2004|loc=para.1}}\n\nHe founded [[Watts & Co.|Watts & Company]] in 1874 along with two other leading 19th century architects: [[George Frederick Bodley]] (the architect of [[Washington National Cathedral]]) and [[Thomas Garner]].\n\nAmong the buildings he designed was [[St John the Baptist Cathedral, Norwich|St John the Baptist Church, Norwich]], which became a [[Roman Catholic]] cathedral.{{sfn|Stamp|2004|loc = para.3}} He was also responsible for buildings in three of the [[University of Cambridge]]'s colleges: [[Christ's College, Cambridge|Christ's]], [[Pembroke College, Cambridge|Pembroke]] and [[Peterhouse, Cambridge|Peterhouse]].<ref>{{citation| url = http://www.cambridge2000.com/cambridge2000/html/architect_builder/George_Gilbert_Scott_the_younger.html |work = Cambridge 2000 project|title= George Gilbert Scott, the younger|accessdate = October 2013}}</ref> He masterminded the main buildings of [[Dulwich College]] in South London. Some of his finest works, the churches of All Hallows, Southwark (1877), and [[St Agnes, Kennington Park|St Agnes, Kennington]] (1880) were destroyed by [[Second World War]] bombing.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://southwark.anglican.org/downloads/lostchurches/KEN03.pdf|title=lost churches of southwark|website=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://londonhistorygroup.com/archives/listings/all-hallows-church-southwark|title=All Hallows church, Southwark|website=|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180509051708/http://londonhistorygroup.com/archives/listings/all-hallows-church-southwark|archive-date=9 May 2018|url-status=dead}}</ref> His best remaining residential work is found in the [[The Avenues, Hull|Avenues area of Kingston upon Hull]], which are in a Queen Anne revival style.<ref name=\"a\">{{citation|url=http://www.hullcc.gov.uk/pls/portal/docs/PAGE/HOME/PLANNING/CONSERVATION/CONSERVATION%20AREAS/AVENUES%20CACA.PDF|title=Urban Conservation and Design: Avenues/Pearson Park Conservation Area: Character Statement for the Avenues part of the above area|publisher=Government of the United Kingdom|accessdate=14 August 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120404031939/http://www.hullcc.gov.uk/pls/portal/docs/PAGE/HOME/PLANNING/CONSERVATION/CONSERVATION%20AREAS/AVENUES%20CACA.PDF|archive-date=4 April 2012|url-status=dead}}</ref> Much of his work was in the [[Queen Anne revival]] style, or in imitation of later Gothic architectural styles.{{sfn|Stamp|2004|loc=para.3 & 4}}\n\nAfter his father died in 1878 he became distant from the architectural business, and was supported by his inheritance.{{sfn|Stamp|2004|loc=para.3}} In 1880 Scott became a [[Roman Catholic]], to the shock of his family. The later part of his life saw his mental stability questioned, and in 1883 he was placed in [[Bethlem Hospital]]. A petition of his brothers and wife resulted in his being found of unsound mind in a public examination in 1884. He escaped to [[Rouen]] in France but, returning to England in 1885, he was confined to hospital again in 1885 and 1891-2.{{sfn|Stamp|2004|loc=paras.5 & 6}}\n\nScott died on 6 May 1897 from [[cirrhosis of the liver]] whilst in residence in the [[Midland Grand Hotel]], St Pancras, which had been designed by his father, and was buried on 11 May 1897 at [[St John-at-Hampstead]].{{sfn|Stamp|2004|loc=para.7}}\n\nHe had six children, four of whom survived past childhood \u2013 two of his sons, Sir [[Giles Gilbert Scott]] and [[Adrian Gilbert Scott]], went on to become noted architects.{{sfn|Stamp|2004|loc=para.7}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Sources==\n*{{Citation\n| title  =Scott, George Gilbert (1839\u20131897), architect and scholar\n|first = Gavin| last = Stamp\n| work = The Oxford Dictionary of National Biography \n| doi = 10.1093/ref:odnb/60773 \n| year = 2004 \n|ref =harv\n}}\n*{{Cite book |author=Stamp, Gavin |authorlink=Gavin Stamp |title=An Architect of Promise: George Gilbert Scott Jr and the Late Gothic Revival |year=2002 |publisher=Shaun Tyas |location= |isbn=978-1-900289-51-1 |page=}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|George Gilbert Scott Junior}}\n*[https://www.theguardian.com/arts/critic/feature/0,1169,856635,00.html Profile of George Gilbert Scott, Jr. in ''The Guardian'']\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Scott, George Gilbert Jr.}}\n[[Category:1839 births]]\n[[Category:1897 deaths]]\n[[Category:People educated at Eton College]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Jesus College, Cambridge]]\n[[Category:Scott family (architects)|George Gilbert Jr.]]\n[[Category:History of mental health in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Deaths from cirrhosis]]\n[[Category:Disease-related deaths in England]]\n[[Category:Gothic Revival architects]]\n[[Category:English ecclesiastical architects]]\n[[Category:English Roman Catholics]]\n[[Category:Converts to Roman Catholicism]]\n[[Category:19th-century English architects]]\n[[Category:Architects from London]]\n", "name_user": "PCWT", "label": "safe", "comment": "Sir Gilbert Scott correctly expressed. He was knighted as Sir Gilbert, not Sir George (see p. 328 of his Recollections).", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/George_Gilbert_Scott_Jr."}
